# March 12 Deliverables: Sequential Code Project Status

We successfully integrated all Fortran modules and completed the delivery requirements for the sequential simulation of the polyethylene chain.

## Implementation Details

[main_serial.f90](./src/main_serial.f90) was implemented to tie together all existing modules and to execute the main Monte Carlo loop directly. The integration:
- Computes energetic contributions using the methods in [energy.f90](./src/lib/energy.f90)
- Updates spatial configurations using the rotation algorithm in [monte_carlo.f90](./src/lib/monte_carlo.f90)
- Exports simulation logs utilizing existing `xyz` manipulation in [io.f90](./src/lib/io.f90)

**Observables Module**: A new module [observables.f90](./src/lib/observables.f90) computes the structural observables:
- End-to-end distance ($R_{ee}$)
- Radius of Gyration ($R_g$)
- Currently realized dihedral angles

**Build Pipeline**: A brand new Makefile in `src/` organizes the compilation process and places all `*.o`, `*.mod`, and `*.x` binaries under `bin/`. 

## Verification Results

We verified the code by running a 1,000,000 step simulation for a 500-carbon linear polymer molecule where the dihedral angle was randomly selected between -$\pi$ and $\pi$.

![Initial Configuration](./img/Serial_500C_InitConf_Screenshot.png)

### Trajectory and Observables

The `results/` folder captures exactly what is required for the March 12th baseline.

#### Energy Evolution
The Lennard-Jones parameters alongside the TraPPE-UA structural torsional energy relax the structure down from the linear extreme correctly.
![Energy Evolution](./img/energy_evolution.png)

#### Torsional Distribution
The code is properly converging on realistic polymer equilibrium limits around gauche/trans configurations across the structure geometry.
![Torsional Distributions](./img/torsion_distribution.png)

#### Radius of Gyration & End-To-End Sequence
Initially set to an ultra-extended 500-Carbon length all-trans format, the polymer shrinks as random MC dihedral modifications introduce folds into a more natural spherical coil distribution over the timescale.
![Evolution of Gyration](./img/observables_evolution.png)

